The expanding target-like erythematous patch, history of camping in an endemic area, and lymphadenopathy suggest the most likely diagnosis is Lyme disease, which is caused by the bite of an infected black-legged tick. Tinea corporis presents with circular, scaly lesions and is not associated with systemic symptoms. Granuloma annulare presents as flesh-colored to erythematous papules or plaques, not target-like. Hansen’s disease (leprosy) presents with hypo/hyperpigmented lesions with loss of sensation, not erythematous target-like lesions.

Tinea corporis is a fungal infection that typically presents as a scaly rash, granuloma annulare is a benign skin condition with no systemic symptoms, and Hansen’s disease (leprosy) typically presents with skin lesions that are hypopigmented and have sensory loss.
